<subSubSection id="C3486534FF95FFF7FF7668B1FC14FB80" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BED36BFFF95FFF7FF7668B1FC14FB80" blockId="114.[151,1127,651,1091]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FF2768B7FE68FD60" authorityName="Czerny" authorityYear="1928" box="[231,426,653,675]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macra">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FF2768B7FE68FD60" box="[231,426,653,675]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">Anthomyza macra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group comprises species with the most plesiomorphic formation of the male and female genitalia (cf. simple apex of nlum, small spines in saccus, presence of setae on medandrium (see 
<figureCitation id="13692A3AFF95FFF7FE1668F1FDF6FD20" box="[470,564,715,739]" captionStart="Figs 239–243" captionStartId="140.[151,188,1413,1432]" captionTargetBox="[166,1090,229,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-11@140.[151,1126,209,1403]" captionTargetPageId="140" captionText="Figs 239–243. Anthomyza silvatica sp. nov., paratype male (Canada: Ontario). 239 – external genitalia, caudally; 240 – the same, frontally (setosity of epandrium omitted); 241–243 – variation of gonostylus, sublaterally (widest extension, micropubescence and/or setosity omitted). Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272933" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272933/files/figure.png" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">Fig. 240</figureCitation>
), separate female S7, simple internal sclerites in the female genital chamber and curved (not twisted) apex of ventral receptacle) and therefore is considered to be the sister group to all remaining 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FD7E6937FCF7FCE0" authorityName="Fallen" authorityYear="1810" box="[702,821,781,803]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FD7E6937FCF7FCE0" box="[702,821,781,803]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">Anthomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF95FFF7FC796931FBA1FCE0" author="ROHACEK J." box="[953,1123,779,803]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 180" refId="ref334979" refString="ROHACEK J. 2009 a: A monograph of Palaearctic Anthomyzidae (Diptera) Part 2. Casopis Slezskeho Zemskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 58 (supplement 1): 1 - 180." type="journal article" year="2009">
ROHÁĆEK 2009 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF95FFF7FB976931FBA1FCE0" author="ROHACEK J. &amp; TOTHOVA A. &amp; VAEHARA J." box="[1111,1123,779,803]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" pagination="49 - 58" refId="ref336555" refString="ROHACEK J., TOTHOVA A. &amp; VAEHARA J. 2009: Phylogeny and afnliation of European Anthomyzidae (Diptera) based on mitochondrial 12 S and 16 S rRNA. Zootaxa 2054: 49 - 58." type="journal article" year="2009">a</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
, ROHÁĆEK et al. 2009). On the other hand, the group is also distinguished by several apomorphies: (1) very broad epandrium; (2) distally dilated gonostylus; (3) saccus of distiphallus with internal coiled strip-like sclerite; (4) very elongate spermathecae. Three Palaearctic species, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FF0469B7FE7BFC60" authority="Czerny, 1928" authorityName="Czerny" authorityYear="1928" box="[196,441,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macra">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FF0469B7FEE6FC60" box="[196,292,909,931]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">A. macra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF95FFF7FEEA69B1FE7BFC60" author="CZERNY L." box="[298,441,907,931]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" refId="ref324799" refString="CZERNY L. 1928: 54 b. Anthomyzidae. In: LINDNER E. (ed.): Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region. Vol. 6, pt. 1. E. Schweizerbartsche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, 8 pp." type="book" year="1928">Czerny, 1928</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FE0269B7FD0DFC60" authority="Czerny, 1928" authorityName="Czerny" authorityYear="1928" box="[450,719,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pleuralis">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FE0269B7FDFFFC60" box="[450,573,909,931]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">A. pleuralis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF95FFF7FD8369B1FD0DFC60" author="CZERNY L." box="[579,719,907,931]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" refId="ref324799" refString="CZERNY L. 1928: 54 b. Anthomyzidae. In: LINDNER E. (ed.): Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region. Vol. 6, pt. 1. E. Schweizerbartsche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, 8 pp." type="book" year="1928">Czerny, 1928</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FCC069B7FBF5FC60" authority="Rohacek, 2009" authorityName="Rohacek" authorityYear="2009" box="[768,1079,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decolorata">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FCC069B7FC53FC60" box="[768,913,909,931]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">A. decolorata</emphasis>
Roháček, 2009
</taxonomicName>
, and three Nearctic species, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FE7F6997FD75FC00" authority="(Loew, 1863)" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[447,695,939,963]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FE7F6997FDDCFC00" box="[447,542,941,963]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">A. tenuis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC34B4EFF95FFF7FDEC6991FD72FC00" author="LOEW H." box="[556,688,939,963]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" pagination="275 - 326" refId="ref328368" refString="LOEW H. 1863: Diptera Americae septentrionalis indigena. Centuria quarta. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift 7: 275 - 326." type="journal article" year="1863">Loew, 1863</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FD036997FCFAFC00" authority="Roháćek &amp; Barber, 2016" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[707,824,941,963]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oblonga" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FD036997FCFAFC00" box="[707,824,941,963]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">A. oblonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21557D6FF95FFF7FC806991FC56FC01" box="[832,916,939,962]" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C524D3CFF95FFF7FC086997FB82FC00" authority="Roháćek &amp; Barber, 2016" authorityName="Roháćek &amp; Barber" authorityYear="2016" box="[968,1088,941,963]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyzidae" genus="Anthomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvatica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B926EAADFF95FFF7FC086997FB82FC00" box="[968,1088,941,963]" italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="111">A. silvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21557D6FF95FFF7FB886991FF07FC21" pageId="114" pageNumber="111" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are currently assigned to the group. Because of their very similar habitus and male and female genitalia, the identincation of some of these species can be difncult. This also causes problems in recognizing interrelationships of all its members, but hypotheses of the afnnities of the Nearctic species are presented in the discussions of each species below.
</paragraph>
